JavaScript:
```javascript
window.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', (event) => {
  const modal = document.querySelector('#staticModal');
  const closeModal = document.querySelector('#closeModal');

  // Open the modal automatically when the page loads
  modal.classList.add('open');

  // Close the modal when the close button is clicked
  closeModal.addEventListener('click', () => {
    modal.classList.remove('open');
  });
});
```

In this code, the `#staticModal` element is selected and the `open` class is added to it on page load, which makes the modal visible. The `#closeModal` button element is selected, and an event listener is attached to it to remove the `open` class when clicked, thus closing the modal.

Note: You need to adjust the CSS classes and styles according to your requirements and preferred styling.

If you are encountering a "Uncaught TypeError: 'set' on proxy: trap returned falsish for property 'isModalVisible'" error when trying to change the value of the `isModalVisible` prop in Vue 3, it means that the property has been defined as readonly or its reactivity has not been properly set up.

To resolve this issue, you need to make sure that the `isModalVisible` prop is reactive and can be mutated. Here are some steps to follow:

1. Make sure you have imported the necessary Vue 3 components and libraries:
```javascript
import { reactive } from 'vue';
```

2. Declare your `isModalVisible` property inside the `data` option of your Vue component, and use the `reactive` function to make it reactive:
```javascript
data() {
  return {
    modal: reactive({
      isModalVisible: true,
    }),
  };
},
```

3. Modify your close button click event handler to update the `isModalVisible` property to `false`:
```javascript
methods: {
  closeModalBox() {
    this.modal.isModalVisible = false;
  },
},
```

4. Update your template to access the `isModalVisible` property from the reactive object and bind it to the visibility of your modal:
```html
<template>
  <div>
    <div v-if="modal.isModalVisible" class="modal">
      <!-- Modal content here -->
      <button @click="closeModalBox">Close</button>
    </div>
    <!-- Rest of your template -->
  </div>
</template>
```

By following these steps and ensuring that the `isModalVisible` property is set up correctly for reactivity, you should be able to change its value to `false` when you click the close button without encountering the "Uncaught TypeError" error.

In Vue 3, you can use the `watch` API to watch for changes to a variable's value. Here's an example of how to watch a variable in Vue 3:

```vue
<template>
  <!-- Your template code -->
</template>

<script>
import { watch } from 'vue';

export default {
  data() {
    return {
      myVariable: 'initial value',
    };
  },
  created() {
    watch(
      () => this.myVariable,
      (newValue, oldValue) => {
        console.log('myVariable changed:', newValue);
        // Perform any desired actions when myVariable changes
      }
    );
  },
};
</script>
```

In this example, we have a variable called `myVariable` in the component's data section. We use the `watch` function to monitor changes to `myVariable` by providing a getter function as the first argument and a callback function as the second argument.

The getter function, `() => this.myVariable`, returns the value of `myVariable`, and the callback function `(newValue, oldValue)` is executed whenever `myVariable` changes. You can then perform any desired actions inside the callback function whenever the value of `myVariable` changes.

Note that the `watch` function is called inside the `created` lifecycle hook to ensure that the watch is set up when the component is created.

You can modify the code as per your requirements to watch a specific variable and perform actions whenever its value changes.

In Vue 3, you don't need to make props reactive explicitly as they are reactive by default. When a prop is passed to a child component, it automatically becomes reactive and triggers reactivity whenever its value changes.

Here's an example of how props work reactively in Vue 3:

```vue
<template>
  <div>
    <p>My prop value: {{ myProp }}</p>
    <button @click="changePropValue">Change Prop Value</button>
  </div>
</template>

<script>
export default {
  props: {
    myProp: {
      type: String,
      required: true,
    },
  },
  methods: {
    changePropValue() {
      this.myProp = 'New Value'; // This will throw an error as props are read-only
    },
  },
};
</script>
```

In this example, we have a child component that receives a prop called `myProp`. The prop is defined in the `props` section, and it is reactive by default. Inside the template, we can directly access and display the prop value using the `{{ myProp }}` syntax.

However, attempting to change the prop value directly within the component, like `this.myProp = 'New Value';`, will result in an error. Props are read-only in Vue and should not be mutated directly within the component that receives them.

If you need to change the value of a prop, you should pass a new value to it from the parent component. The parent component can handle the state or data changes and then pass the updated value to the child component as a prop. This way, the child component's reactive nature will automatically come into play, updating itself when the prop value changes in the parent.

I apologize for the confusion. In Vue 3, props are indeed read-only and should not be mutated directly within the child component.

To change a prop value in response to a button click in the child component, you can emit an event to notify the parent component of the desired change. The parent component can then update the prop value and pass it back to the child component. Here's an updated example:

ChildComponent.vue:
```vue
<template>
  <div>
    <p>My prop value: {{ myProp }}</p>
    <button @click="changePropValue">Change Prop Value</button>
  </div>
</template>

<script>
export default {
  props: {
    myProp: {
      type: String,
      required: true,
    },
  },
  methods: {
    changePropValue() {
      this.$emit('update:myProp', 'New Value');
    },
  },
};
</script>
```

ParentComponent.vue:
```vue
<template>
  <div>
    <child-component :my-prop="myProp" @update:myProp="myProp = $event" />
  </div>
</template>

<script>
import ChildComponent from './ChildComponent.vue';

export default {
  components: {
    ChildComponent,
  },
  data() {
    return {
      myProp: 'Initial Value',
    };
  },
};
</script>
```

In this example, when the button is clicked in the child component, the `changePropValue()` method emits an event using `this.$emit()`. The event is named `'update:myProp'` and passes the new value (`'New Value'`) as the argument.

The parent component (which renders the child component) listens to the event using `@update:myProp="myProp = $event"` in the template. When the event is emitted, the parent component updates `myProp` with the new value passed via `$event`.

As a result, the child component receives the updated `myProp` value as a prop, triggering reactivity and reflecting the new value within the child component template.

With this approach, you can pass updated values to props by emitting events and handling the changes in the parent component.

